article.description: Tangela Smith scored 17 points and had eight rebounds to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to an 81-71 win Sunday over the Washington Mystics.
article.headline: Monarchs bench rules with 37 points
article.linkText: Smith, Walker lift Monarchs to second straight
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Rebekkah Brunson helped Sacramento's
bench play a big role.

She scored a season-high 12 points and Tangela Smith scored 17
points and had eight rebounds to lead the Monarchs to an 81-71 win
Sunday over the Washington Mystics.

"I'm practicing against some of the best post players in the
league every day," Brunson said. "It makes you ready."

Brunson led a 37-point effort from the Sacramento reserves.
Ruthie Bolton scored eight points and Kara Lawson had seven.

DeMya Walker scored 12 points, and had seven rebounds and seven
assists for the Monarchs, who won for the second time in two days.
Yolanda Griffith added 11 points and seven rebounds.

"They were getting a lot of offensive rebounds on us in the
first half," Smith said. "We ran more in the second half and
played aggressive defense. And our bench is really coming together.
They have been coming up big the last few games."

Washington rookie Alana Beard scored 27 points and Chamique
Holdsclaw, the WNBA's second-leading scorer, had 25 points and 10
rebounds. The Mystics have lost three of four.

Trailing the entire first half, the Monarchs went on a 17-4 run
early in the second, erasing a seven-point deficit to take a 60-54
lead on a reverse layup by Bolton with 8:37 remaining.

"We couldn't put two good halves together," Washington coach
Michael Adams said.
